result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (5th) and Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (5th) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs) was dismissed by the court.

  • Shari Jn Schoenemann was found guilty of OWI (5th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Associated with Charge #1

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Additional statements by: Susan N.

The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  3.5 YEARS with 0 days credit CONCURRENT to any other sentence; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1.5 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.

Court finds defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program and the Earned Release program.  

Conditions of Extended Supervision:
- Court allows for transfer to Florida to complete supervision.
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- Absolute/maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs.
- No possession/consumption/selling/distribution of illegal drugs/alcohol.
- Random urine screens.
- Obtain/maintain fulltime employment/education/vocation.
- Provide a DNA sample.
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.

Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
Fine in the amount of $1,800.00; 
All court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA); 
All applicable fees of supervision.
-  Cash bail on deposit to apply
-  The Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.

Court ordered defendant's operating privileges revoked for 3 YEARS with the mandatory reinstatement fee.  

Defendant's operating privilege for operation of Class D vehicles is restricted to operating vehicles that are equipped with an ignition interlock device; and each motor vehicle for which the defendant's name appears on the vehicle's certificate of title or registration must be equipped with an ignition interlock device beginning on the date the department issues any license and for a period of  1 YEAR  thereafter.

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon she may never possess a firearm. 
Court advised defendant of his right to seek postconviction relief.
Court advised defendant that she may not vote until her civil rights have been restored.

Defendant Shari Jn Schoenemann in court with attorney Michael F. Bishop.  Defendant Shari Jn Schoenemann in custody.  Thomas L. Potter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Pursuant to negotiations, Counts 2-5 were dismissed.  Count 1 is amended to OWI 5th within 5 years.  As to Count 1:
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon she may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that her voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
